c forenames:  German Erwin, Herta.","English (Kent): variant of <b>Dench</b>, an ethnic name for someone from Denmark, from Middle English <i>denshe</i>, <i>dench</i> ‘Danish’ (Old English <i>denisc</i>). There were many Danes in England in the Middle Ages, not only the long-established settlers in the Danelaw region, but also more recent immigrants."],"variants":[{"name":"Denmark","meanings":["English (Norfolk): ethnic name denoting someone from Denmark (see   Dence  ). In the British Isles this name is found mainly in East Anglia.","Americanized form of German <b>Dennemark</b>, ethnic name for someone from Denmark, from Middle Low German <i>Dennemarken</i>."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Enguerrand II d'Encre was born in 1275, in Europe, his father, Othon D’Encre, was 30 and his mother, Mathilde de ROSIÈRES, was 22. He married Blanche de Rubempré. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1329, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1275–1329":"1275–1329","1278–1334":"1278–1334","1296–1348":"1296–1348","1245–1299":"1245–1299","1253–1309":"1253–1309","1348":"1348","1334":"1334","1245":"1245","1278":"1278","1299":"1299","1275":"1275","1253":"1253","1296":"1296","1309":"1309","1329":"1329","Albert, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Albert, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Europa":"Europe"},"fi":{"1275–1329":"1275–1329","1278–1334":"1278–1334","1296–1348":"1296–1348","1245–1299":"1245–1299","1253–1309":"1253–1309","1348":"1348","1334":"1334","1245":"1245","1278":"1278","1299":"1299","1275":"1275","1253":"1253","1296":"1296","1309":"1309","1329":"1329","Albert, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Albert, Somme, Picardie, Ranska","Europa":"Europe"},"fr":{"1275–1329":"1275–1329","1278–1334":"1278–1334","1296–1348":"1296–1348","1245–1299":"1245–1299","1253–1309":"1253–1309","1348":"1348","1334":"1334","1245":"1245","1278":"1278","1299":"1299","1275":"1275","1253":"1253","1296":"1296","1309":"1309","1329":"1329","Albert, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Albert, Somme, Picardie, France","Europa":"Europe","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Enguerrand II d'Encre est né en 1275, à Europe, son père, Othon D’Encre, avait 30 ans et sa mère, Mathilde de ROSIÈRES, avait 22 ans. Il a épousé Blanche de Rubempré. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé en 1329, à l’âge de 54 ans."},"de":{"1275–1329":"1275–1329","1278–1334":"1278–1334","1296–1348":"1296–1348","1245–1299":"1245–1299","1253–1309":"1253–1309","1348":"1348","1334":"1334","1245":"1245","1278":"1278","1299":"1299","1275":"1275","1253":"1253","1296":"1296","1309":"1309","1329":"1329"